WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.211
The barn doors were heavier than they looked. Noor had

00:00:03.211 --> 00:00:06.421
to brace her shoulder against the left one and push

00:00:06.421 --> 00:00:09.632
with both legs, and the door moved on its track

00:00:09.632 --> 00:00:12.842
with a sound like an animal waking — a low

00:00:12.842 --> 00:00:16.053
groan, then a rumble, then daylight pouring across the concrete

00:00:16.053 --> 00:00:19.263
floor in a widening band that caught the dust she

00:00:19.263 --> 00:00:22.474
had disturbed and held it, spinning, in the air. She

00:00:22.474 --> 00:00:25.684
stood in the doorway and let her eyes adjust. The

00:00:25.684 --> 00:00:28.895
space was taller than she had expected. The timber frame

00:00:28.895 --> 00:00:32.105
rose to a peak thirty feet overhead, the beams hand-hewn

00:00:32.105 --> 00:00:35.316
— she could see the adze marks, the grain opened

00:00:35.316 --> 00:00:38.526
and roughened by the blade, each timber carrying the evidence

00:00:38.526 --> 00:00:41.737
of the hand that shaped it. Cross-braces formed Xs between

00:00:41.737 --> 00:00:44.947
the posts, and the whole structure had the particular beauty

00:00:44.947 --> 00:00:48.158
of engineering that predates calculation: proportions arrived at by instinct

00:00:48.158 --> 00:00:51.368
and inheritance, by generations of people who understood that a

00:00:51.368 --> 00:00:54.579
building's strength lives in its connections. Light entered through clerestory

00:00:54.579 --> 00:00:57.789
windows set high in the east and west walls, throwing

00:00:57.789 --> 00:01:01.000
long parallelograms across the floor. The floor itself was concrete,

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:04.210
poured over what looked like the original stone foundation, and

00:01:04.210 --> 00:01:07.421
it bore the marks of decades of use — oil

00:01:07.421 --> 00:01:10.632
stains, paint drips, the ghost of a chalk line someone

00:01:10.632 --> 00:01:13.842
had snapped and never swept away. Along the north wall,

00:01:13.842 --> 00:01:17.053
a workbench ran the full length of the space, its

00:01:17.053 --> 00:01:20.263
surface scarred and warped. Above it, a pegboard held the

00:01:20.263 --> 00:01:23.474
shadows of tools that had been removed: the clean rectangles

00:01:23.474 --> 00:01:26.684
where hammers and saws and clamps had hung, surrounded by

00:01:26.684 --> 00:01:29.895
the gray patina of dust and age. The loft was

00:01:29.895 --> 00:01:33.105
accessed by a steep staircase — not a ladder, a

00:01:33.105 --> 00:01:36.316
proper staircase with treads and a railing, though the treads

00:01:36.316 --> 00:01:39.526
were worn to splinters at the leading edge. She did

00:01:39.526 --> 00:01:42.737
not go up yet. She stood in the center of

00:01:42.737 --> 00:01:45.947
the floor and turned in a slow circle and felt

00:01:45.947 --> 00:01:49.158
the space the way she always felt a new space

00:01:49.158 --> 00:01:52.368
— with her whole body, the way a tuning fork

00:01:52.368 --> 00:01:55.579
feels the note it was made for. She had never

00:01:55.579 --> 00:01:58.789
had a studio. This fact, which she had learned to

00:01:58.789 --> 00:02:02.000
state casually in grad school critiques and artist residency applications

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.210
— I've always worked in shared spaces, it keeps me

00:02:05.210 --> 00:02:08.421
honest — was not casual. It was the central fact

00:02:08.421 --> 00:02:11.632
of her working life. She had made sculpture in her

00:02:11.632 --> 00:02:14.842
mother's garage in Fort Bragg, in a shared ceramics studio

00:02:14.842 --> 00:02:18.053
at RISD where she was allocated six hours a week,

00:02:18.053 --> 00:02:21.263
in an unheated storage unit in Providence that she rented

00:02:21.263 --> 00:02:24.474
for four months until the landlord found out she was

00:02:24.474 --> 00:02:27.684
using a blowtorch. She had made work on kitchen tables

00:02:27.684 --> 00:02:30.895
and in bathtubs and on the fire escape of a

00:02:30.895 --> 00:02:34.105
fourth-floor walkup where she dried clay pieces on the metal

00:02:34.105 --> 00:02:37.316
grating and prayed it wouldn't rain. She had learned to

00:02:37.316 --> 00:02:40.526
work small because she had to work small. Her MFA

00:02:40.526 --> 00:02:43.737
thesis was a series of palm-sized objects — river stones

00:02:43.737 --> 00:02:46.947
wrapped in copper wire, each wire shaped to follow the

00:02:46.947 --> 00:02:50.158
topography of the stone it held. The faculty had called

00:02:50.158 --> 00:02:53.368
them "intimate" and "considered" and "a meditation on the tension

00:02:53.368 --> 00:02:56.579
between containment and form." One professor, the one she respected,

00:02:56.579 --> 00:02:59.789
had looked at them for a long time and then

00:02:59.789 --> 00:03:03.000
said, "What would you make if you had room?" She

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.210
hadn't answered. She hadn't known. The barn was the size

00:03:06.210 --> 00:03:09.421
of the gymnasium at the middle school in San Diego

00:03:09.421 --> 00:03:12.631
where she had spent seventh grade, which had also been

00:03:12.631 --> 00:03:15.842
the size of the chapel at Fort Drum where she

00:03:15.842 --> 00:03:19.053
had spent part of fifth grade, both of which she

00:03:19.053 --> 00:03:22.263
remembered primarily as volumes — the height of the ceiling,

00:03:22.263 --> 00:03:25.474
the echo of her footsteps, the way a large space

00:03:25.474 --> 00:03:28.684
could make a person feel both liberated and exposed. She

00:03:28.684 --> 00:03:31.895
had spent her childhood moving through spaces she did not

00:03:31.895 --> 00:03:35.105
own, in houses her family did not choose, on bases

00:03:35.105 --> 00:03:38.316
where everything belonged to someone else and could be taken

00:03:38.316 --> 00:03:41.526
back with thirty days' notice. By the time she was

00:03:41.526 --> 00:03:44.737
sixteen, she had lived in nine houses in six states,

00:03:44.737 --> 00:03:47.947
and she had learned to move through rooms without touching

00:03:47.947 --> 00:03:51.158
the walls. Now she touched the wall. She pressed her

00:03:51.158 --> 00:03:54.368
palm flat against the limestone foundation, which was cool and

00:03:54.368 --> 00:03:57.579
slightly damp, and felt the grit of the mortar between

00:03:57.579 --> 00:04:00.789
the stones. She ran her hand along the timber post

00:04:00.789 --> 00:04:04.000
beside it — smooth where shoulders and hands had worn

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.210
the wood over decades, rough where the bark had been

00:04:07.210 --> 00:04:10.421
left on, the cambium still visible in places, the tree

00:04:10.421 --> 00:04:13.631
still legible inside the beam. She walked the perimeter. Along

00:04:13.631 --> 00:04:16.842
the south wall, a set of double doors opened onto

00:04:16.842 --> 00:04:20.053
the meadow — she unlatched them and pushed one open,

00:04:20.053 --> 00:04:23.263
and the air that came through smelled of frost and

00:04:23.263 --> 00:04:26.474
grass and the mineral sweetness of the creek that ran

00:04:26.474 --> 00:04:29.684
somewhere below the bluff. From here she could see the

00:04:29.684 --> 00:04:32.895
back of the main house, the greenhouse with its glass

00:04:32.895 --> 00:04:36.105
panels catching the morning light, and beyond it the line

00:04:36.105 --> 00:04:39.316
of cottages half-hidden in the trees. The landscape was still

00:04:39.316 --> 00:04:42.526
new enough to startle her — the scale of it,

00:04:42.526 --> 00:04:45.737
the green persistence of the cedars against the brown and

00:04:45.737 --> 00:04:48.947
gold of the hardwoods, the way the sky sat heavily

00:04:48.947 --> 00:04:52.158
on the hills like something you could lean against. She

00:04:52.158 --> 00:04:55.368
closed the door. Not all the way — she left

00:04:55.368 --> 00:04:58.579
it cracked, the way she left all doors, a habit

00:04:58.579 --> 00:05:01.789
her mother had attributed to the cat they'd had in

00:05:01.789 --> 00:05:05.000
Fayetteville and which Noor knew was actually about knowing she

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.210
could get out. ... By noon, she had cleared the

00:05:08.210 --> 00:05:11.421
workbench. It was not clean work. The bench had accumulated

00:05:11.421 --> 00:05:14.631
years of debris — rusted nails, bent screws, a coffee

00:05:14.631 --> 00:05:17.842
can of bolts frozen together with corrosion, rags stiff with

00:05:17.842 --> 00:05:21.052
dried linseed oil, a tangle of baling wire, half a

00:05:21.052 --> 00:05:24.263
tube of caulk, a hand-drawn map of something (the property?

00:05:24.263 --> 00:05:27.474
the plumbing?) on a piece of cardboard so warped with

00:05:27.474 --> 00:05:30.684
moisture that the lines had become abstract. She sorted everything

00:05:30.684 --> 00:05:33.895
into piles: keep, discard, uncertain. The uncertain pile was the

00:05:33.895 --> 00:05:37.105
largest. She had always been better at acquiring materials than

00:05:37.105 --> 00:05:40.316
getting rid of them. Underneath the debris, the bench surface

00:05:40.316 --> 00:05:43.526
was beautiful. Maple, she thought, though it could have been

00:05:43.526 --> 00:05:46.737
beech — a dense, pale hardwood with a grain so

00:05:46.737 --> 00:05:49.947
tight it was almost invisible, its surface marked with the

00:05:49.947 --> 00:05:53.158
honest damage of use. Saw cuts, chisel marks, the rings

00:05:53.158 --> 00:05:56.368
left by coffee mugs and paint cans. She ran her

00:05:56.368 --> 00:05:59.579
fingers across these marks the way you run your fingers

00:05:59.579 --> 00:06:02.789
across the grooves in a vinyl record — reading the

00:06:02.789 --> 00:06:06.000
history by touch. She found other things as she cleared.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:09.210
A drawer built into the bench contained a set of

00:06:09.210 --> 00:06:12.421
wood chisels in a leather roll, their edges still sharp,

00:06:12.421 --> 00:06:15.631
the handles darkened with hand oil. A second drawer held

00:06:15.631 --> 00:06:18.842
files and rasps of various coarseness, arranged by size. In

00:06:18.842 --> 00:06:22.052
a cabinet beneath the bench, a hand plane with a

00:06:22.052 --> 00:06:25.263
rosewood body and a blade that, when she tested it

00:06:25.263 --> 00:06:28.473
against her thumbnail, bit cleanly. These were not abandoned tools.

00:06:28.473 --> 00:06:31.684
They were waiting tools — stored with care by someone

00:06:31.684 --> 00:06:34.895
who expected them to be used again. Eleanora's? Or someone

00:06:34.895 --> 00:06:38.105
before her. The tools had the patina of long use,

00:06:38.105 --> 00:06:41.316
the kind of relationship between hand and handle that takes

00:06:41.316 --> 00:06:44.526
years to develop. Noor held the plane in both hands

00:06:44.526 --> 00:06:47.737
and felt its weight and balance and understood that whoever

00:06:47.737 --> 00:06:50.947
had used this tool had loved it in the way

00:06:50.947 --> 00:06:54.158
you love something by wearing it out — not preciously,

00:06:54.158 --> 00:06:57.368
but completely. She set the plane on the bench and

00:06:57.368 --> 00:07:00.579
took out her phone and photographed it, and then the

00:07:00.579 --> 00:07:03.789
chisels, and then the bench itself, and then the light

00:07:03.789 --> 00:07:07.000
falling through the clerestory windows onto the concrete floor. She

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.210
was not documenting. She was doing what she always did

00:07:10.210 --> 00:07:13.421
in a new space: collecting evidence that it was real.

00:07:13.421 --> 00:07:16.631
... She heard him before she saw him. Boots on

00:07:16.631 --> 00:07:19.842
gravel, then on concrete — a heavy, deliberate step, the

00:07:19.842 --> 00:07:23.052
gait of someone who carried weight not because he was

00:07:23.052 --> 00:07:26.263
large but because he had spent years carrying things. Callan

00:07:26.263 --> 00:07:29.473
appeared in the open doorway, framed by the light behind

00:07:29.473 --> 00:07:32.684
him so that for a moment he was only a

00:07:32.684 --> 00:07:35.895
shape — broad shoulders, hands at his sides, the particular

00:07:35.895 --> 00:07:39.105
stillness of a person who stops at a threshold and

00:07:39.105 --> 00:07:42.316
waits. "Sorry," he said. "I didn't know anyone was in

00:07:42.316 --> 00:07:45.526
here." "You don't have to be sorry. It's not my

00:07:45.526 --> 00:07:48.737
barn." He stepped inside and looked around, and she watched

00:07:48.737 --> 00:07:51.947
his eyes do what hers had done an hour earlier

00:07:51.947 --> 00:07:55.158
— move up the timber frame, reading the structure. But

00:07:55.158 --> 00:07:58.368
where she had felt the space as volume, she could

00:07:58.368 --> 00:08:01.579
see that he was reading it as engineering. His gaze

00:08:01.579 --> 00:08:04.789
tracked the joints, the bracing, the way the loads traveled

00:08:04.789 --> 00:08:08.000
from the ridge beam down through the posts to the

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.210
foundation. He reached out and put his hand on the

00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:14.421
nearest timber the way a doctor puts a hand on

00:08:14.421 --> 00:08:17.631
a patient's chest — not touching, exactly, but assessing. "White

00:08:17.631 --> 00:08:20.842
oak," he said. "The whole frame. That's unusual. Most barns

00:08:20.842 --> 00:08:24.052
are a mix — whatever was closest to the mill."

00:08:24.052 --> 00:08:27.263
"Is it old?" "The frame is. Eighteen-eighties, maybe earlier. It's

00:08:27.263 --> 00:08:30.473
been repointed — the foundation mortar's newer. And the roof

00:08:30.473 --> 00:08:33.684
was done in the last twenty years. But the bones

00:08:33.684 --> 00:08:36.894
are original." He tilted his head back and looked up

00:08:36.894 --> 00:08:40.105
into the peak. "Someone put a lot of thought into

00:08:40.105 --> 00:08:43.316
this." "I found tools under the bench. Chisels, a hand

00:08:43.316 --> 00:08:46.526
plane." He walked over and she showed him. He picked

00:08:46.526 --> 00:08:49.737
up the plane, held it the way she had —

00:08:49.737 --> 00:08:52.947
with both hands, testing the weight — and turned it

00:08:52.947 --> 00:08:56.158
over to look at the sole. "Norris," he said. "English.

00:08:56.158 --> 00:08:59.368
This is worth real money." "I'm not going to sell

00:08:59.368 --> 00:09:02.579
it." He looked at her, and something shifted in his

00:09:02.579 --> 00:09:05.789
face. Not a smile. A recognition, maybe — the slight

00:09:05.789 --> 00:09:09.000
easing that comes when you discover someone speaks a language

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.210
you thought only you knew. "I didn't think you were,"

00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:15.421
he said. He set the plane down with the precision

00:09:15.421 --> 00:09:18.631
of someone who understood that how you put a tool

00:09:18.631 --> 00:09:21.842
down was as important as how you picked it up.

00:09:21.842 --> 00:09:25.052
Then he unrolled the leather case and examined each chisel,

00:09:25.052 --> 00:09:28.263
holding them up to the clerestory light, turning them slowly.

00:09:28.263 --> 00:09:31.473
"These have been used hard," he said. "But maintained. Somebody

00:09:31.473 --> 00:09:34.684
dressed these edges recently — last few years, at least."

00:09:34.684 --> 00:09:37.894
He paused. "Eleanora?" "That's what I wondered." "June would know."

00:09:37.894 --> 00:09:41.105
They were both quiet for a moment, standing at the

00:09:41.105 --> 00:09:44.316
bench with the tools between them. Noor was aware that

00:09:44.316 --> 00:09:47.526
this was the longest conversation she'd had with Callan —

00:09:47.526 --> 00:09:50.737
the longest conversation she'd had with anyone here, unless you

00:09:50.737 --> 00:09:53.947
counted Fen's monologues, which she didn't, because a monologue was

00:09:53.947 --> 00:09:57.158
not a conversation. Callan seemed to communicate in a different

00:09:57.158 --> 00:10:00.368
register than the others — less verbal, more spatial. He

00:10:00.368 --> 00:10:03.579
occupied a room the way a piece of furniture occupies

00:10:03.579 --> 00:10:06.789
a room: solidly, without apology, aware of its own dimensions.

00:10:06.789 --> 00:10:10.000
"What are you going to make?" he asked. "I don't

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.210
know yet." He nodded. This was, she understood, the right

00:10:13.210 --> 00:10:16.421
answer. He did not follow up with questions about her

00:10:16.421 --> 00:10:19.631
process or her medium or her artistic statement, the questions

00:10:19.631 --> 00:10:22.842
she had been asked at every critique and every residency

00:10:22.842 --> 00:10:26.052
and every grant panel, the questions that assumed the work

00:10:26.052 --> 00:10:29.263
was a product of decisions when in fact the work

00:10:29.263 --> 00:10:32.473
was a product of listening — listening to the material,

00:10:32.473 --> 00:10:35.684
the space, the strange accumulation of accidents and intentions that

00:10:35.684 --> 00:10:38.894
brought a particular stone or piece of timber into your

00:10:38.894 --> 00:10:42.105
hands at the moment you were ready to receive it.

00:10:42.105 --> 00:10:45.315
"The frame could use some work," Callan said. He pointed

00:10:45.315 --> 00:10:48.526
to a joint where two beams met a post. "That

00:10:48.526 --> 00:10:51.737
brace is carrying too much load. The tenon's pulled —

00:10:51.737 --> 00:10:54.947
see the gap? Quarter inch, maybe more. If it slips,

00:10:54.947 --> 00:10:58.158
the whole bay shifts." She looked where he was pointing.

00:10:58.158 --> 00:11:01.368
She could see the gap now, a dark line between

00:11:01.368 --> 00:11:04.579
the timbers where daylight shouldn't be. "Can you fix it?"

00:11:04.579 --> 00:11:07.789
"I'd need to jack the bay, pull the brace, cut

00:11:07.789 --> 00:11:11.000
a new tenon. Three days, maybe four. I'd have to

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.210
work around whatever you're doing in here." "I'm not doing

00:11:14.210 --> 00:11:17.421
anything yet." "You're clearing the bench. That's doing something." She

00:11:17.421 --> 00:11:20.631
looked at him. His face, in the diffused light of

00:11:20.631 --> 00:11:23.842
the barn, was impassive in the way that certain landscapes

00:11:23.842 --> 00:11:27.052
are impassive — not blank but layered, the expression composed

00:11:27.052 --> 00:11:30.263
of so many small things that the sum was unreadable

00:11:30.263 --> 00:11:33.473
unless you were willing to stand still long enough to

00:11:33.473 --> 00:11:36.684
see them resolve. "Fix the joint," she said. "I'll work

00:11:36.684 --> 00:11:39.894
around you." ... Over the next three days, the barn

00:11:39.894 --> 00:11:43.105
became a shared workspace in the way that shared workspaces

00:11:43.105 --> 00:11:46.315
actually work: not through negotiation or scheduling but through the

00:11:46.315 --> 00:11:49.526
gradual accommodation of two people's rhythms. Callan arrived early, before

00:11:49.526 --> 00:11:52.736
Noor was awake, and she would find evidence of his

00:11:52.736 --> 00:11:55.947
morning's work when she came in after breakfast — sawdust

00:11:55.947 --> 00:11:59.158
on the floor, a timber propped at an angle, the

00:11:59.158 --> 00:12:02.368
jack positioned under the bay with the care of someone

00:12:02.368 --> 00:12:05.579
who understood that a hydraulic jack supporting ten thousand pounds

00:12:05.579 --> 00:12:08.789
of structure was not something you left to chance. She

00:12:08.789 --> 00:12:12.000
worked around him. Or alongside him. The distinction blurred. She

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.210
had cleared the bench and begun to gather materials: a

00:12:15.210 --> 00:12:18.421
limestone cobble from the creek bed, a piece of red

00:12:18.421 --> 00:12:21.631
oak that had fallen from one of the trees along

00:12:21.631 --> 00:12:24.842
the drive, a shard of glass she had found at

00:12:24.842 --> 00:12:28.052
the base of the greenhouse — thick, bottle-green, its edges

00:12:28.052 --> 00:12:31.263
softened by years of weather. She laid these on the

00:12:31.263 --> 00:12:34.473
bench and arranged them and rearranged them and stood back

00:12:34.473 --> 00:12:37.684
and looked and then moved them again. She did not

00:12:37.684 --> 00:12:40.894
know what she was making. She was in the stage

00:12:40.894 --> 00:12:44.105
she thought of as gathering, which looked, from the outside,

00:12:44.105 --> 00:12:47.315
like nothing, and felt, from the inside, like the most

00:12:47.315 --> 00:12:50.526
important work she would do. Callan did not ask what

00:12:50.526 --> 00:12:53.736
she was doing. He glanced at the bench sometimes, the

00:12:53.736 --> 00:12:56.947
way a person glances at a book someone else is

00:12:56.947 --> 00:13:00.158
reading — with interest but without the presumption of comment.

00:13:00.158 --> 00:13:03.368
Once, he picked up the limestone cobble, turned it in

00:13:03.368 --> 00:13:06.579
his hand, and set it back down without a word.

00:13:06.579 --> 00:13:09.789
She appreciated this more than she could have explained. In

00:13:09.789 --> 00:13:13.000
grad school, every object on her worktable had been subject

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:16.210
to interrogation: What's the intention? What's the referent? How does

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:19.421
this relate to your practice? The questions were not wrong,

00:13:19.421 --> 00:13:22.631
exactly, but they arrived too early, like guests who show

00:13:22.631 --> 00:13:25.842
up before the party is ready, and their presence changed

00:13:25.842 --> 00:13:29.052
the nature of what she was doing — turned an

00:13:29.052 --> 00:13:32.263
act of discovery into a performance of discovery. In the

00:13:32.263 --> 00:13:35.473
barn, with Callan working twenty feet away, there was no

00:13:35.473 --> 00:13:38.684
performance. There was only the work. On the second day,

00:13:38.684 --> 00:13:41.894
while he was fitting a new tenon into the repaired

00:13:41.894 --> 00:13:45.105
brace, she asked him about his grandfather's farm. He was

00:13:45.105 --> 00:13:48.315
holding the timber in place with one hand and adjusting

00:13:48.315 --> 00:13:51.526
the jack with the other, his body balanced in a

00:13:51.526 --> 00:13:54.736
way that made the effort look natural, and for a

00:13:54.736 --> 00:13:57.947
moment she thought he hadn't heard her. Then he said,

00:13:57.947 --> 00:14:01.157
"Wheat, mostly. Some cattle. Hundred sixty acres outside Enid, Oklahoma."

00:14:01.157 --> 00:14:04.368
"Is it still there?" "The land is. The buildings burned

00:14:04.368 --> 00:14:07.579
in 'ninety-four. I was nine." She waited. He lowered the

00:14:07.579 --> 00:14:10.789
brace into position, checked the alignment with a square he'd

00:14:10.789 --> 00:14:14.000
pulled from his back pocket, and tapped it with a

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.210
mallet — once, twice, a third time, each tap accompanied

00:14:17.210 --> 00:14:20.421
by a tilt of his head as he listened to

00:14:20.421 --> 00:14:23.631
the sound the wood made, the resonance changing as the

00:14:23.631 --> 00:14:26.842
joint tightened. "My grandfather built that barn himself. Forty years

00:14:26.842 --> 00:14:30.052
old, no plans, just knew how it was supposed to

00:14:30.052 --> 00:14:33.263
go. Post and beam, hand-cut, same as this. After the

00:14:33.263 --> 00:14:36.473
fire, there was nothing left above the foundation. The concrete

00:14:36.473 --> 00:14:39.684
slab was still warm three days later." He stepped back

00:14:39.684 --> 00:14:42.894
and looked at the joint. Nodded once, to himself. "I

00:14:42.894 --> 00:14:46.105
started building things after that. Couldn't tell you why, exactly.

00:14:46.105 --> 00:14:49.315
I was nine years old and my grandfather's barn had

00:14:49.315 --> 00:14:52.526
burned and I started building things out of scrap wood

00:14:52.526 --> 00:14:55.736
in the backyard and I haven't stopped." Noor was sitting

00:14:55.736 --> 00:14:58.947
on the bench with her legs drawn up, the limestone

00:14:58.947 --> 00:15:02.157
cobble in her lap, turning it slowly in her hands.

00:15:02.157 --> 00:15:05.368
The stone was cool and dense and she could feel

00:15:05.368 --> 00:15:08.579
the grain of it — the layers of sediment compressed

00:15:08.579 --> 00:15:11.789
over millennia, the fossilized fragments of creatures so old they

00:15:11.789 --> 00:15:15.000
were no longer recognizable as creatures, just patterns in the

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.210
rock. "My family moved every two years," she said. "Sometimes

00:15:18.210 --> 00:15:21.421
less. My dad was Army. Fort Bragg, Fort Drum, Fort

00:15:21.421 --> 00:15:24.631
Hood, San Diego, Okinawa for a year. I went to

00:15:24.631 --> 00:15:27.842
nine schools before high school." Callan was wiping the sawdust

00:15:27.842 --> 00:15:31.052
from the joint with a rag, his movements slow and

00:15:31.052 --> 00:15:34.263
thorough. "I started making things because they were the only

00:15:34.263 --> 00:15:37.473
things that came with me," she said. "Everything else —

00:15:37.473 --> 00:15:40.684
the house, the neighborhood, the friends — all of that

00:15:40.684 --> 00:15:43.894
got left behind. But the things I made, I could

00:15:43.894 --> 00:15:47.105
put them in a box and carry them." She held

00:15:47.105 --> 00:15:50.315
up the cobble. "Now I make things that are too

00:15:50.315 --> 00:15:53.526
heavy to carry. I haven't figured out what that means

00:15:53.526 --> 00:15:56.736
yet." He looked at her across the barn — the

00:15:56.736 --> 00:15:59.947
full width of the space between them, the dust motes

00:15:59.947 --> 00:16:03.157
drifting in the columns of light, his hands still on

00:16:03.157 --> 00:16:06.368
the timber he had just repaired. "Maybe it means you're

00:16:06.368 --> 00:16:09.578
ready to stay somewhere," he said. It was the most

00:16:09.578 --> 00:16:12.789
words she had heard him speak at once. They landed

00:16:12.789 --> 00:16:16.000
in the barn's silence the way a stone lands in

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.210
water — a brief disturbance, then the ripples moving outward,

00:16:19.210 --> 00:16:22.421
the surface resettling into something that looked the same but

00:16:22.421 --> 00:16:25.631
wasn't. She set the cobble on the bench beside the

00:16:25.631 --> 00:16:28.842
glass and the red oak. She did not answer, because

00:16:28.842 --> 00:16:32.052
the answer, if she had one, was too close to

00:16:32.052 --> 00:16:35.263
the truth to say out loud to someone she'd known

00:16:35.263 --> 00:16:38.473
for four days. But she held it the way she

00:16:38.473 --> 00:16:41.684
held the stone — turning it over, feeling its weight,

00:16:41.684 --> 00:16:44.894
sensing the shape of the thing it might become. ...

00:16:44.894 --> 00:16:48.105
By the end of the first week, the barn had

00:16:48.105 --> 00:16:51.315
begun to change. Callan's repair was done — the bay

00:16:51.315 --> 00:16:54.526
squared, the brace tight, the whole structure newly stable in

00:16:54.526 --> 00:16:57.736
a way she could feel underfoot, the faint give that

00:16:57.736 --> 00:17:00.947
had been in the floor now gone. He had also

00:17:00.947 --> 00:17:04.157
replaced two clerestory panes that had cracked and rehung the

00:17:04.157 --> 00:17:07.368
south doors so they swung true. He did this without

00:17:07.368 --> 00:17:10.578
announcement or expectation of thanks, the way rain fills a

00:17:10.578 --> 00:17:13.789
creek bed — because that was the direction things flowed.

00:17:13.789 --> 00:17:16.999
Noor's bench was covered now. She had been walking the

00:17:16.999 --> 00:17:20.210
property every morning, sometimes twice, and bringing back what she

00:17:20.210 --> 00:17:23.421
found: more limestone, a section of walnut branch with a

00:17:23.421 --> 00:17:26.631
burl that looked like a clenched fist, a coil of

00:17:26.631 --> 00:17:29.842
rusted barbed wire from the south fence line, a piece

00:17:29.842 --> 00:17:33.052
of slate from the creek bed that rang like a

00:17:33.052 --> 00:17:36.263
bell when she struck it. She laid everything out and

00:17:36.263 --> 00:17:39.473
photographed it and moved the pieces in relation to each

00:17:39.473 --> 00:17:42.684
other and stood at different distances and waited. She was

00:17:42.684 --> 00:17:45.894
not ready to make. She was ready to know what

00:17:45.894 --> 00:17:49.105
to make, which was different. On Friday, she walked to

00:17:49.105 --> 00:17:52.315
the greenhouse to look at the glass. The greenhouse was

00:17:52.315 --> 00:17:55.526
attached to the south side of the main house, a

00:17:55.526 --> 00:17:58.736
structure of iron and glass that must have been elegant

00:17:58.736 --> 00:18:01.947
once and was now in a state of beautiful decline

00:18:01.947 --> 00:18:05.157
— several panels cracked, the iron frame rusted in places,

00:18:05.157 --> 00:18:08.368
the interior overgrown with plants that had survived the previous

00:18:08.368 --> 00:18:11.578
winter without tending. Lena was inside, kneeling in the dirt,

00:18:11.578 --> 00:18:14.789
pulling weeds from a raised bed with the focused intensity

00:18:14.789 --> 00:18:17.999
of someone performing a task they understood to be both

00:18:17.999 --> 00:18:21.210
necessary and therapeutic. "You're the sculptor," Lena said, without looking

00:18:21.210 --> 00:18:24.421
up. "I'm Noor." "I know. You're the sculptor." Lena sat

00:18:24.421 --> 00:18:27.631
back on her heels and pushed her hair from her

00:18:27.631 --> 00:18:30.842
face with the back of her wrist. "June told me

00:18:30.842 --> 00:18:34.052
about the barn. She said you've been collecting materials." "That's

00:18:34.052 --> 00:18:37.263
one word for it." "What's another?" Noor leaned against the

00:18:37.263 --> 00:18:40.473
greenhouse doorframe. The glass above her was intact here, and

00:18:40.473 --> 00:18:43.684
the light came through it green-tinged and warm, carrying the

00:18:43.684 --> 00:18:46.894
smell of damp soil and something herbal — thyme, maybe,

00:18:46.894 --> 00:18:50.105
gone wild along the edge of the bed. "Listening," she

00:18:50.105 --> 00:18:53.315
said. "I'm listening to the property. Trying to hear what

00:18:53.315 --> 00:18:56.526
it wants to give me." Lena regarded her for a

00:18:56.526 --> 00:18:59.736
moment. Her expression was hard to read — not skeptical,

00:18:59.736 --> 00:19:02.947
not indulgent, but appraising, the way a nurse appraises a

00:19:02.947 --> 00:19:06.157
patient who has just described a symptom in unexpected language.

00:19:06.157 --> 00:19:09.368
"That's a nice way to put it," Lena said. "Most

00:19:09.368 --> 00:19:12.578
people show up to a new place and try to

00:19:12.578 --> 00:19:15.789
impose something on it. You're waiting for it to offer."

00:19:15.789 --> 00:19:18.999
"I've lived in enough places to know that imposing doesn't

00:19:18.999 --> 00:19:22.210
work." Lena went back to weeding. Her hands moved through

00:19:22.210 --> 00:19:25.420
the soil with a practiced ease, finding the roots by

00:19:25.420 --> 00:19:28.631
feel, drawing them out with a steady pressure that was

00:19:28.631 --> 00:19:31.842
more persuasion than force. Noor watched her and thought about

00:19:31.842 --> 00:19:35.052
hands — how Callan's hands read a timber joint, how

00:19:35.052 --> 00:19:38.263
Lena's hands read soil, how her own hands read stone

00:19:38.263 --> 00:19:41.473
and clay and the surfaces of things. There was a

00:19:41.473 --> 00:19:44.684
language in it, a way of knowing the world that

00:19:44.684 --> 00:19:47.894
had nothing to do with words, and she wondered if

00:19:47.894 --> 00:19:51.105
this was what had drawn all of them here —

00:19:51.105 --> 00:19:54.315
not the letter, not the stipend, not the vague promise

00:19:54.315 --> 00:19:57.526
of a year's pause, but some shared intuition that they

00:19:57.526 --> 00:20:00.736
had been living too much in their heads and not

00:20:00.736 --> 00:20:03.947
enough in their hands. "There's a broken panel on the

00:20:03.947 --> 00:20:07.157
west side," Noor said. "The glass is thick. Old. I've

00:20:07.157 --> 00:20:10.368
been looking at it." Lena stopped weeding. "You want the

00:20:10.368 --> 00:20:13.578
broken glass?" "If no one's going to repair it." "Callan

00:20:13.578 --> 00:20:16.789
said he'd fix the greenhouse next. After the barn." "I

00:20:16.789 --> 00:20:19.999
don't want the whole panel. Just the broken piece. The

00:20:19.999 --> 00:20:23.210
one on the ground." Lena looked at her, and something

00:20:23.210 --> 00:20:26.420
passed between them — not understanding, exactly, but the willingness

00:20:26.420 --> 00:20:29.631
to trust that understanding would come. "Take it," she said.

00:20:29.631 --> 00:20:32.842
"It's just going to cut someone otherwise." Noor walked to

00:20:32.842 --> 00:20:36.052
the west side of the greenhouse and picked up the

00:20:36.052 --> 00:20:39.263
shard. It was the size of a dinner plate, thick,

00:20:39.263 --> 00:20:42.473
its edges scalloped where it had broken, the glass green

00:20:42.473 --> 00:20:45.684
and wavering like water. She held it up to the

00:20:45.684 --> 00:20:48.894
light and the world through it bent and shifted, the

00:20:48.894 --> 00:20:52.105
trees and sky reorganized into something liquid, something that hadn't

00:20:52.105 --> 00:20:55.315
decided yet what shape to take. She carried it back

00:20:55.315 --> 00:20:58.526
to the barn and set it on the bench beside

00:20:58.526 --> 00:21:01.736
the limestone and the oak and the wire and the

00:21:01.736 --> 00:21:04.947
slate. She stood back. The materials lay before her in

00:21:04.947 --> 00:21:08.157
no particular arrangement, each one carrying its own history —

00:21:08.157 --> 00:21:11.368
the stone, millions of years old; the wood, decades; the

00:21:11.368 --> 00:21:14.578
glass, maybe a century; the wire, rusted to the color

00:21:14.578 --> 00:21:17.789
of dried blood. Each one taken from the property. Each

00:21:17.789 --> 00:21:20.999
one offered, not taken. She had asked the land and

00:21:20.999 --> 00:21:24.210
the land had answered, and now the answer lay on

00:21:24.210 --> 00:21:27.420
a maple workbench in a white oak barn, waiting for

00:21:27.420 --> 00:21:30.631
her to hear the question. She picked up the hand

00:21:30.631 --> 00:21:33.841
plane — Eleanora's, or whoever's — and held it, feeling

00:21:33.841 --> 00:21:37.052
the weight, the warm rosewood body, the blade's sleeping edge.

00:21:37.052 --> 00:21:40.263
Then she set it down and opened her sketchbook and

00:21:40.263 --> 00:21:43.152
began, for the first time since arriving, to draw.
